  "texts": [
    "In machine ethics, this has inspired the development of divine-command logic, where human input is interpreted as divine command for the machine (Bringsjord and Taylor 2012).",
    "For contractualists stemming from Kantian thought, justified principles require instead that they are agreed upon by everyone (Rawls 1980), or that no-one could reasonably reject them (Scanlon 2000).",
    "Contractualism puts emphasis on the rationality of agents, which, following Kant's moral rationalism, requires that we respect others in the sense that principles must be justified to each person.",
    "By contrast, contractarians stemming from Hobbesian thought-e.g., Gauthier (1987) and Narveson (2001) -puts emphasis on the self-interests of agents, in the sense that moral rules ought to maximize the joint interest.",
    "Thus, for contractarianism, adherence to moral norms or rules are justified on the basis of an agent's self-interest; and altruism occurs when the agent recognizes that the best way to maximize their self-interest is to cooperate with others."
  ],
